<p>Georgia's solar resource potential ranks among the top 15 states nationally, with excellent conditions for photovoltaic energy generation. The state receives an average of 4.9 peak sun hours daily, with significant seasonal variation ranging from approximately 3.2 hours in December to 6.8 hours in June. This solar irradiance translates to annual energy production of roughly 1,300-1,450 kWh per installed kilowatt of solar capacity, depending on system orientation, tilt angle, and local shading conditions.</p>

<p>The optimal solar panel orientation in Georgia is due south with a tilt angle between 25-35 degrees to maximize year-round energy production. However, east and west-facing installations can still achieve 85-90% of optimal production, making solar viable for homes with various roof configurations. Georgia's relatively stable weather patterns, with minimal severe weather events that could damage solar installations, contribute to consistent energy production and long system lifespans typically exceeding 25 years.</p>

<p>Seasonal production patterns in Georgia align well with energy consumption needs, as peak solar production occurs during summer months when air conditioning drives the highest electricity usage. This natural correlation between solar generation and energy demand helps maximize the value of solar investments by offsetting the most expensive peak-rate electricity consumption periods.</p>

