<h2>HVAC Systems in Georgia</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Georgia's humid subtropical climate presents unique challenges and requirements for HVAC systems. The state experiences hot, humid summers with average temperatures in the mid-80s to low-90s Fahrenheit, combined with relative humidity levels often exceeding 70%. This combination creates substantial cooling loads that can strain inefficient HVAC systems and drive electricity bills significantly higher during the extended cooling season from May through September.</p>

<p>Winter heating requirements in Georgia are moderate, with average temperatures ranging from the mid-30s to mid-50s Fahrenheit. However, occasional cold snaps can push temperatures below freezing, requiring reliable heating systems. The moderate heating loads make heat pump systems particularly attractive in Georgia, as they can provide both efficient cooling and heating while consuming less energy than traditional electric resistance heating or gas furnaces for most of the year.</p>

<p>High humidity levels throughout much of the year make dehumidification capability crucial for HVAC systems in Georgia. Proper humidity control not only improves comfort but also prevents mold and mildew growth, protects indoor air quality, and can allow for higher thermostat settings while maintaining comfort levels. Modern HVAC systems with variable-speed components and enhanced dehumidification capabilities are particularly well-suited to Georgia's climate conditions.</p>

